Broken Symmetries 
We have seen that for the truncated KK theory, at
tree level, certain amplitudes are protected and others are not.
This is not just because of 5D momentum conservation, which is
present even in the minimal discretization. The calculations in
Section  were done after choosing a unitary gauge for the 5D
metric  (see l5d4d . This gauge is unitary 
because it leads to a tower of 4D
massive gravitons, each with 5 polarizations, which is the
right number of propagating degrees of freedom for a massless 5D graviton.
This gauge was useful for both calculating amplitudes and exploring
the truncated KK theory in the site basis. However, 
the strong scattering amplitudes we uncovered then have no clear
interpretation from the 5D point of view.
Instead, we can explore the truncated KK theory without gauge
fixed, where it comprises a
tower of tensors, vectors, and scalars
coming from ,  and , respectively.
Now there are apparently 9 degrees of freedom at each mass level,
and unitarity violations can be understood from the scattering of
any of the unphysical 4. 

First, let us look at the 4D symmetries, which we expect to hold
exactly after the truncation. In unitary gauge, we could contrive
to have  4D GC symmetries manifest and exact by introducing
Goldstone bosons in the site basis. If no gauge is fixed, the symmetries
must be already present. A GC symmetry acts on  as
. The gauge field
for these symmetries is .
We can decompose the 5D symmetry into a tower of 4D symmetries:
^(x,z) =  _n^e^2 i  n z R  
Under these transformations, the KK towers for a scalar 
shift as:
^n = ^(n-j)  _^j These symmetries mix  modes, but are diagonal in the site basis.
We can see that  is exactly preserved after the truncation
by taking the indices in 4dGC  to be defined only modulo 
(the discrete Fourier transform of the symmetries in the site basis).
The Ward identities for these symmetries protect all the amplitudes
involving the production of longitudinal modes of .

The broken symmetry is the reparameterization of
: , with gauge field .
Because  is the discretized dimension, this transformation acts
differently from 4dGC  on towers. For example,
